ick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Robert Ashington was born about 1124, in Chilton, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Sir. Robert Ashington Baron. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"Abt 1124–":"umbes 1124–Surnud","1120–1190":"1120–1190","1150–1230":"1150–1230","1124–Female":"1124–Surnud","1190":"1190","Abt 1150":"umbes 1150","Abt 1124":"umbes 1124","1124":"1124","1230":"1230","1120":"1120","1150":"1150","Bramber, Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"Bramber, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ashington Manor, Chilton, England":"Chilton, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1124–":"noin 1124–Kuollut","1120–1190":"1120–1190","1150–1230":"1150–1230","1124–Female":"1124–Kuollut","1190":"1190","Abt 1150":"noin 1150","Abt 1124":"noin 1124","1124":"1124","1230":"1230","1120":"1120","1150":"1150","Bramber, Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"Bramber, Sussex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Ashington Manor, Chilton, England":"Chilton, Oxfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1124–":"environ 1124–Décédée","1120–1190